{
  "chapter_number": 14,
  "chapter_title": "Structures and Unions",
  "sections": [
    {
      "section_title": "Introduction",
      "keywords": ["structures", "unions"],
      "content": "Structures and unions are user-defined data types used to group related data."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "What is a Structure?",
      "keywords": ["structure definition"],
      "content": "A structure is a user-defined data type that allows storing variables of different data types under a single name."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Need for Structures",
      "keywords": ["importance"],
      "content": [
        "Store related information together",
        "Represent real-world entities",
        "Improve code organization"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Structure Declaration",
      "keywords": ["structure syntax"],
      "content": "struct Student\n{\n int roll;\n char name[20];\n float marks;\n};"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Structure Variable Declaration",
      "keywords": ["structure variable"],
      "content": "struct Student s1;"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Accessing Structure Members",
      "keywords": ["dot operator"],
      "content": "Structure members are accessed using the dot (.) operator."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Structure Initialization",
      "keywords": ["initialization"],
      "content": "struct Student s1={1,\"Suhani\",89.5};"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Nested Structures",
      "keywords": ["nested structure"],
      "content": "A structure inside another structure is called a nested structure."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Array of Structures",
      "keywords": ["array of structures"],
      "content": "Multiple structure variables can be stored in an array."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Pointer to Structure",
      "keywords": ["structure pointer"],
      "content": "Pointers can store addresses of structure variables."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Arrow Operator (->)",
      "keywords": ["arrow operator"],
      "content": "The arrow operator accesses structure members through a pointer."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "What is a Union?",
      "keywords": ["union definition"],
      "content": "A union is a user-defined data type where all members share the same memory location."
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Union Declaration",
      "keywords": ["union syntax"],
      "content": "union Data\n{\n int i;\n float f;\n char ch;\n};"
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Features of Union",
      "keywords": ["union features"],
      "content": [
        "Shared memory",
        "Memory efficient",
        "Only one member stores a valid value at a time"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Difference Between Structure and Union",
      "keywords": ["comparison"],
      "content": [
        "Structures allocate separate memory for each member.",
        "Unions share the same memory among all members.",
        "Structures use more memory.",
        "Unions use less memory."
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Advantages of Structures",
      "keywords": ["structure advantages"],
      "content": [
        "Stores multiple data types",
        "Represents complex records",
        "Improves code readability"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Applications",
      "keywords": ["applications"],
      "content": [
        "Student Records",
        "Employee Management Systems",
        "Database Applications",
        "Inventory Systems"
      ]
    },
    {
      "section_title": "Example Program",
      "keywords": ["program"],
      "content": "#include <stdio.h>\n\nstruct Student\n{\n int roll;\n};\n\nint main()\n{\n struct Student s1;\n s1.roll=101;\n printf(\"%d\",s1.roll);\n return 0;\n}"
    }
  ],
  "summary": [
    "Structures group different data types.",
    "Members are accessed using the dot operator.",
    "Unions share memory among members.",
    "Arrow operator is used with structure pointers.",
    "Structures and unions are widely used in real-world applications."
  ]
        }
